69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I thought that Document.load was a no-go due to backwards compatibility (introducing "load" in variable scope of scripts that didn't have it before). But I can't find any concrete evidence 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: no-op? By saying "no-go", I meant that exposing load() on HTML documents may be unacceptable for compatibility 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: so FWIW, Document===XMLDocument + existing XMLDocumentLoader.load still seems like a good plan to me 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: unless some vendor wants to test the waters with Document.load 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: that Sarissa thing seems pretty unique, although admittedly rather common on the Web 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: introducing Document.load might the best path overall indeed. Hopefully someone remembers if there were actual known compatibility issues with that 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: that's an interesting combination of ideas that I didn't consider. It's pretty far from what WebKit implements now, so I can't confidently say that it's OK for us, but it seems OK 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: it's the "Regular XML documents <‚Ä¶> keep returning a regular Document object" part that I found new

createDocument().load() is definitely not a no-op dunno about Document.load() in general ah, yeah, that's possible having XMLDocument.load not be the actual load() is not web compatible (webkit goes down a number of fallback codepaths because of that) 62c428533830d84fd8bc77bf402512fc: it would mean "load()" would refer to document.load() and not window.load() in all event handler attributes (e.g. onload="load()" would change meaning) so you're probably right that it's a no-go. a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9, where does the spec say that?  It says that text fields have their own selections, but not that selecting text in text fields doesn't also select it in the browsing context.  Am I missing something? It just says that the UA should allow the user to change the selection. "This one selection must be shared by all the content of the browsing context (though not by nested browsing contexts), including any editing hosts in the document."\ s/\\// Firefox and WebKit seem to have the more plausible interpretation to me. Ugh, faked browser UI in Chrome: http://www.huffingtonpost.com/stewart-abercrombie-baker/smallpox-in-the-garage_b_596340.html Evil. They could have done better by using position: fixed. a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9, well, the spec says that the UA should provide a means for the user to change the selection, not that it has to make sense.  Clearly, this is merely a quality-of-implementation issue, and everyone passes. Well, perhaps Firefox has simply chosen to interpret page load as a user choice of selection. This is what happens when you leave UI totally undefined, am I right?  :) Whee.

88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: Firefox seems weird to me 88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: Looks to me like Firefox claims there's a zero-length selection at a random location in the document... When there's no selection at all The spec also says "Returns null if there's no selection." Which firefox does not If at any point you (or a script) have selected anything, it never forgets E.g. select some random text, remove the selection, and it claims there's a zero-length selection at the start of the ex-selection If there is no ex-selection (such as in that test), it picks body for some reason Never mind It picks the parent of the input the script selected But the offsets are 1, not the offset of the input http://dashiva.net/test/selection.html

JonathanMalek - a lot of this has been learned by experience from some of the re-use of existing formats in microformats, e.g. vCard in hCard, and Atom in hAtom many of the MUSTS/requirements of the original formats made it into the respective microformats - but even then it was obvious that the source formats were too burdensome to authors too many artificial musts/requireds and thus both hCard and hAtom made some properties *optional* that were required in the source formats, by denoting good algorithms for synthesizing required properties when necessary but even with a reduction of number of required properties (as compared to the source formats), there have *still* been numerous examples where the requirements have gotten in the way of publishing (or parsing) and with people making up values for the "required" properties, like "anonymous" as a value for author in hAtom in hCard, I created a bunch of optimizations for easier web publishing, but experience has shown than even more optimizations ( = fewer required properties, more flexibility) are both necessary and useful one of my first public observations about this required/MUST problem was this tweet: http://twitter.com/t/status/3293046574 ... and yes - I should write this up on a wiki page. braindumping in IRC for now to at least give you the thinking that is going on, and raw material for the logs (from which a page can be written) a couple more tweets on this topic: http://twitter.com/t/status/3631221162 http://twitter.com/t/status/3631366361

jgraham, re your test, I did some similar testing recently for array index properties http://www.w3.org/mid/<email/> jgraham, and I think the answer should depend on what comes out of that thread the current way that named/indexed properties are handled sucks a bit it's a little awkward having to look at what own properties already exist on the object, whether they're configurable or not, etc., so that they can be explicitly overwritten having a [[Get]] & [[Put]] layer over the top of the object seems cleaner and easier to understand I did change the spec to this "looking at what properties exist on the object and having real properties set on the object when collection elements are added" way because TC39 folks were unhappy with the custom [[Get]]/[[Put]] semantics that used to exist in the spec but now they seem to be ok with it (with the Proxy proposal moving forward) jgraham, so to answer a slightly different question: what I want that test to log is true, [object HTMLImageElement], true

Next steps: Larry: let's see if we can get more attendees & agenda items for next interim meeting." it seems end users would want to mute a video, but not necessarily want to unmute it so having muted just be an author thing seems fine to me forgot .muted currently reflects the end user setting yeah me too I think .muted should just turn into an author setting like it is for Flash video as well mute control on youtube can say it should give sound, but I often have it turned off system wide anyway 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, I guess in that case mutating the DOM might be ok, though I am not sure 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, for <details> UAs could remember the state too which would mutate the DOM isn't it the same problem for <details>? author assumes it is open/closed but it's the other way around based on earlier interaction (or maybe a preference/extension that expands all those controls by default) the styling would only be affected if the user agent remembered the muted settings, I wonder how likely such a scenario is is it worth the trouble? however, having muted and .defaultMuted also works for me 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, I meant following the <input value> design 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, sicking is right that it's not nice, but it would be internally consistent and somewhat predictable and not give weird DOM stuff (though in the case of <details> it would require a pseudo-class of some kind to be introduced) might be interesting well, <details> is not stuck yet

sounds like a useful meeting i dunno, having to type defaultmuted="" defaultvolume="0.5" defaultplaybackrate="2" seems more annoying than muted="" volume="0.5" playbackrate="2" pointers to defaultValue unpopularity? (would it be less unpopular if the attribute was called defaultvalue=""?) foolip: what do you think? ^ from the author's perspective, he mutes the video if he adds the attribute sure 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: on a second thought, maybe it's not so bad to just mutate the dom why is it weird? if the author wants special styling for muted videos, it makes sense to have video[muted] match when the video is muted it seems stupid to hook that styling off muted="", and anyway youtube would want to use a different video stream for those to save bandwidth, and could just remove the audio stream altogether and not bother with muted="" what if the author only has the main video and wants to style it specially when it's muted we could introduce :muted for that, but having [muted] just work is simpler true edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: it seems like better user experience to remember the mute setting on reload edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: remembering checkbox states is apparently worth the trouble although a form taken together can take a long time to fill, while muting a video is trivial so i dunno i'm not an UX guy :) s/an/a/ seems bad to ship 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e experiments with known bad design that are impossible to revert later on if it is bad design can't we already test this since some versions of ie mutate the dom? maybe we can get help from the html5 doctors here post a simplequiz Which Way Sucks Less? summons the doctors that would be a function of what works in existing browsers so when we know the answer it's too late to change the feature

aren't they all cc097e0d7183ae8436e7df709553c8c0: re http://www.w3.org/Bugs/Public/show_bug.cgi?id=10419#c7 , value->defaultValue has proven really unpopular, which is why i am skeptical of doing it for that one what i really want is an attribute where we can stick all the "initial state" stuff default playback rate, volume, muted... except only support muted for now i guess autoplay is already its own thing and automute doesn't really sound right i agree not sure what to do search for "The HTML DOM got this very wrong" in http://lists.whatwg.org/htdig.cgi/whatwg-whatwg.org/2010-September/028755.html it would be less unpopular with sicking if value="" was the default value and editing muted the DOM i'm not personally convinced that's great either though mutated not muted :-) the other thing is that this isn't an attribute whose values are "muted" and "not muted", it's an attribute whose values are "mute initially in all cases" and "use the user's default for this video" so "muted" isn't necessarily the most obvious name it should also be pointed out that a lot of people don't think we should have the mute/volume state be remembered on a per-video basis and that instead we should have a browser-level mute (maybe per tab) that can't be controlled by JS, and that video.muted should only be the author override for the video but that would make the video's mute indicator and the system mute indicator not be the only indicators of relevance, instead adding at least one more to the mix which i'm not sure is a good idea end users? or authors? i almost never want videos muted personally, if i want audio off i want all audio off and turn it off at the system level i'd love a "this tab is a source of sound" indicator, but i don't think i care about turning the sound off at that level (though a shortcut to override all the <video> elements on the page in one go mighht be ok) i don't understand, are you saying that .muted should not reflect the muted indicator you get from controls=""? i think mutating the dom would be really weird for the reason given by the CSS example I gave in http://lists.whatwg.org/htdig.cgi/whatwg-whatwg.org/2010-September/028755.html (that problem isn't such a big deal for <details>) i would expect a difference because an author might have a bunch of muted videos that are always muted, and he uses that as a hook for styling them differently from the main video that isn't muted e.g. imagine if the small poster frames on a youtube page were all live <video>s muted ones and they were made small because all muted videos were small that's different than <details> and [open] because the most likely reason to style [open] is that you're trying to do something for when it's open vs when it's not but i agree that this argument is weak yeah i'm not saying it'd be a good idea that argues for exposing the entire API in content attributes i'm not sure that's a reasonable line of argumentation fwiw, flash apparently makes a mess of this particular issue (muting by default), so they're not useful as inspiration here. cc097e0d7183ae8436e7df709553c8c0 is right that defaultmuted="" is kinda ugly ah sicking would hate that thinks that remembering mute state may be more important for some settings than remembering checked state, btw :-) yeah, <details> is kind of my experiment in this space i want to see what authors think of the straight-DOM-mutation design well it's not known bad, that's the point the IE experiment suggested it might be good, but was confused because authors were more annoyed with the lack of interop than either particular behaviour. that would certainly be interesting, but it's more the organic blog rants and how many pages use it and so on that i am interested in e.g. finding how many people use [open] vs how many people detect onopen and set a class or whatnot yes it's a long-term experiment yeah, <details> is stuck this way forever. the point is to find out the results for future ideas.

b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: interesting the results you got with your performance changes b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: because in hubbub, I was briefly toying with having a buffer only when required and switching to it if NULs/CRs/entities were encountered b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: turns out it added a lot of extra macros, removed clarity, and it ended up easier and about as fast to do unconditional buffer writes I wish I knew x86 well enough to speculate on why it's the case that's pretty speedy Hubbub's tokeniser tokenises HTML5 in about 0.5s which is something like 5MB/s however, libxml tokenises and produces a tree in 0.8s.  so there's quite a lot of scope for improvement, or so I hope I have some perf tests around which basically mmap() a file into memory and then pass the memory thus mapped to libxml2/hubbub I guess I could read an entire file properly rather than letting the OS do it, but I don't think it would make that much difference at some point it would be nice to do proper somewhat-scientific benchmarks, though right now getting hubbub fully-funtional takes more priority my benchmarking is really unscientific, and consists of writing test apps and running them through `time` on the command-line otoh, mmap() after a couple of runs results in fairly unchanging data, so it's good enough for me yeah, you have the advantage there :)

b07211a0c7cb119232799d2119cea90f: I guess it's comforting that C is like that, too, and this isn't just a Java thing ;-) today, I measured the perf cost of the HTML5 tree builder compared to an XML-ish tree builder I'll blog about that later executive summary: the Validator.nu HTML Parser's tokenizer is almost as fast as Xerces without the HTML tree builder complexity b07211a0c7cb119232799d2119cea90f: do you count IO when benchmarking the tokenizer? with Java, IO details make a huge difference which is why I run benchmarks from RAM when I don't want to benchmark IO (I already tweaked IO earlier) (It might not be a bad idea to rerun tests with IO included) I do timing inside Java and warm the VM up first performance tuning on HotSpot is pretty annoying because doing the wrong thing can lead to HotSpot not JITting stuff which means about tenth the performance I wonder how much I could speed up the tokenizer if I removed all the run-time configurability

hmm. 587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef thinks we can go from CR to REC in just 13 months. How do you expect to produce a comprehensive test suite and achieve 2 interoperable implementations of the whole spec within that time? define "good enough"? CSS 2.1 has been CR for several years now (though it went back to WD in between) it looks like it was first published as CR in 2004 I'm referring to the time it is taking for CSS2.1 to be interoperably implemented also CSS2.0 went Rec in 1998 (before the CR phase was introduced in the W3C), so that's been nearly 10 years and we still don't have 2 interoperable implementations 587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef, of course. Implementation and testing is currently going on. But it's taking a long time isn't particularly interested in using RDF and GRDDL as examples 587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef, roughly how many test cases would you estimate we would need for the whole spec?  (just a rough figure to the nearest 1000 or so) I just don't understand why you're being so persistent with your estimates, despite getting feedback about them being unrealisting on several occasions. *unrealistic I think we all want to get finished.  I just want to be realistic. 587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef, your estimates have always been fairly close to those given in the charter, varying only by a few months so in order to get done by your time frame, you would suggest moving some features to HTML6, and publishing a smaller HTML5?

yup the key is to build tests as we address issues we have a lot of test materials in progress I don't expect to produce a comprehensive test suite; just a good-enough test suite experience will define good enough checks the charter and finds "comprehensive test suite". hmm. oh well; that's still subject to judgement I plan to do the best test suite we can in the next year or two assertion-based testing isn't all that valuable in my experience; I don't mind if somebody does it I don't think CSS is a good example of how to manage the W3C process I've done several timely test suites: RDF Core, OWL, SPARQL, and GRDDL. I'm reasonably happy with all of those, though their scope is hundreds of times smaller than HTML's I expect a massively parallel testing and QA effort for HTML isn't particularly interested in using CSS as an example b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9, we have a lot of recruiting to do, indeed. But we don't need to write *that* many tests. The bulk of the manual labor is in reporting test results. f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220, there's no way to make a compelling argument about how long something will take. June 2009 is my best guess based on what I know today. Maybe in a few months I'll know different. I think I've estimated 15,000 to 50,000 test cases. because I want to get finished, and repeating something does make it come true. I'm not sure what you mean by "so persistent". I've changed my estimates several times I want to be realistic too; keep in mind that postponing features to a later release is always an option, and often a good one. yes "need" is a strong word. we need to advance the state of the art; we don't need to solve all problems in one rev yes, e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0 ; we should focus testing effort toward that end that's why assertion testing is less interesting to me; there's little bang-for-the-buck in writing test cases for stuff that is already interoperably deployed there's still _some_ value in it, and I hope somebody does it. but it's not a high priority the test suite will be in some state of readiness as we go to CR a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554, indeed, it's easier to be sure with more data.

would count comprehensive at checking every possible if statement in HTML 5 we need to define current browser features, even if no more. 587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef: as someone who would like to create a HTML UA, yet someone who doesn't have huge amounts of time to spend reverse engineering current behaviour, it seems pointless to not define something interoperability 587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef: I'd question how you can be sure the stuff is interoperably deployed without test suites

587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef: is there a good example that we should learn from? 587bf8b858e15d03428e1415c33c38ef: It seems to me we lack a massive number of competent and willing test case writers I'm sure given politics at the time, DTDs had to be in XML, but wow they sure are a pain for implementations

test results are hardly the issue creating the tests and getting implementors to fix the bugs is always has been the issue also, going from CR to REC in 13 months seems optimistic if the test suite isn't ready by the time we go to CR (and even then it would be optimistic) sure, they're in some state of readyiness now :) i guess we'll see how it goes

E.g., transform: scale(2) rotate(0); is the same as transform: scale(2) rotate(0deg);, not a parse error. This is not what CSS Values and Units says. Has this been discussed?  Should I mail www-style? All implementations seem to agree. is looking That was my recollection. 171db427cee236fc04af9e5de94e7c39, why isn't it a Values and Units bug?  "0" can already be either <number> or <length>, why not <angle> too? So it's really just futureproofing, or we have a property where it matters? 88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: Yes, I know.  It's an impl bug in Transforms that's unfixable at this point.  Transforms needs to explicitly define that. Because it creates more possibilities for ambiguity. It would have been a problem for an earlier draft of gradient syntax, for example. So we have existence proof of problems. (The gradient syntax issue was that one of the arguments could, among other things, be either "<length> <length>" or "<length> <angle>".) With significantly different behavior based on which way the 0 was translated.) Even unitless lengths sometimes cause problems - it means we always need to ensure that a property that accepts lengths and numbers gives the exact same interpretation to "0" for both types. yep It's an ESXi 5 Cluster which can migrate VMs from overloaded hosts and  where the hosts have 10Gbs connections to the NetApp storage that is distinct from the other network connections. That compares to the common scenario before where there was at most 1Gbps network adapter than was used for all network access including the NetApps disk storage. I don't know that I've experienced too much migration so far apart from some tests. I think the biggest issue was fixing the networking. The benefit for the migration is not getting into a situation where some hosts are perenially overloaded while others sit idle. I would imagine with a fairly constant load the VMs will distribute across the hosts and not continually move around. 42bea5914051e9a2d1dcddcc986a4fad: Dan Parsons is the go to guy for esx and the cluster I'm on. I recommend talking to him. I think the perceptions people have built up about VMs might be out of date when they are deployed properly. I think there is a good chance for a win for you guys.

is http://::0123:dead:feed:babe/ a valid URL? Or should that be http://[::0123:dead:feed:babe]/ instead? (safari handles those two URLs differently) yes, i know ;) safari says "can't find server 0123" when I try to load http://::0123:dead:feed:babe/ but it works nicely when loading the same, with [] around the IP address yes... i was confused by safari's behaviour nope... Safari's handling is correct "To comply with RFC 2732, literal IPv6 address in URLs must be enclosed in [ and ] characters." quoting from the RFC: To use a literal IPv6 address in a URL, the literal address should be enclosed in "[" and "]" characters. yes. once a RFC is publishes, it cannot be changed... which kinda sucks I wish RFCs were available in a cleaner format not these old 70s text files
